---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'nomad-needs', text: 'What Digital Nomads Need', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Digital Nomad Visa Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'location-independence', text: 'True Location Independence', level: 2 },
  { id: 'tech-lifestyle', text: 'Tech and Lifestyle Coverage', level: 2 },
  { id: 'common-mistakes', text: 'Common Mistakes to Avoid', level: 2 },
  { id: 'choosing-plan', text: 'Choosing the Right Plan', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { href: '/best/remote-worker-insurance', text: 'Remote Worker Insurance' },
  { href: '/best/adventure-sports-insurance', text: 'Adventure Sports Coverage' },
  { href: '/visas/digital-nomad-visa/in/portugal', text: 'Portugal DNV' },
  { href: '/visas/digital-nomad-visa/in/spain', text: 'Spain DNV' },
  { href: '/best/short-term-expat-insurance', text: 'Short-Term Coverage' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'flexibility', header: 'Flexibility' },
  { key: 'visaCompliant', header: 'DNV Compliant' },
  { key: 'telemedicine', header: 'Telemedicine' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Monthly Cost' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  {
    provider: 'SafetyWing',
    flexibility: 'Excellent',
    visaCompliant: 'Most countries',
    telemedicine: 'Included',
    price: '$42-84',
  },
  {
    provider: 'World Nomads',
    flexibility: 'Good',
    visaCompliant: 'Most countries',
    telemedicine: 'Basic',
    price: '$100-180',
  },
  {
    provider: 'Cigna Global',
    flexibility: 'Moderate',
    visaCompliant: 'All countries',
    telemedicine: 'Full platform',
    price: '$150-350',
  },
  {
    provider: 'Genki',
    flexibility: 'Excellent',
    visaCompliant: 'Most countries',
    telemedicine: 'Included',
    price: '$35-70',
  },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Digital Nomad Insurance 2026 | Location-Independent Coverage"
  description="Health insurance designed for digital nomads. Compare flexible plans that work across countries, meet visa requirements, and adapt to the nomadic lifestyle."
  headline="Best Insurance for Digital Nomads"
  subheadline="Traditional insurance assumes you have an address. Digital nomad insurance assumes you don't. Here's coverage built for people who work from anywhere."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Nomad Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/safetywing"
>
  <p class="text-lg mb-8">
    Digital nomad insurance isn't just travel insurance with better marketing. It's coverage designed for people who work remotely from different countries, have no permanent address, and need flexibility above all else. Here's what actually works for the nomadic lifestyle.
  </p>

  <h2 id="top-picks" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Our Top Picks for Digital Nomads</h2>

  <p class="mb-4">
    These providers understand that nomads need flexibility, affordability, and coverage that crosses borders without paperwork.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">SafetyWing — Best Overall for Digital Nomads</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The good:</strong> SafetyWing was literally built for digital nomads. Subscription model ($42/month) means no annual commitment. Sign up from anywhere—you don't need to be home. Coverage works in 180+ countries. Includes home country visits (30 days per 90). Two children free per adult. Cancel anytime.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Travel medical, not comprehensive health coverage. $250,000 limit. Pre-existing conditions excluded. US coverage limited. Routine care not covered. Adventure activities have restrictions.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Most digital nomads—especially those under 40 who are healthy and prioritize flexibility and affordability.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Genki — Best European Alternative</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The good:</strong> German-based insurer with plans designed for nomads. Competitive pricing starting around €35/month. Good European network. Monthly subscription like SafetyWing. Meets most digital nomad visa requirements in Europe.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Less established than SafetyWing. Network stronger in Europe than elsewhere. Similar travel medical limitations. Smaller community and less third-party validation.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Best for:</strong> European nomads or those spending significant time in Europe who want an alternative to SafetyWing.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">World Nomads — Best for Adventure Nomads</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The good:</strong> Covers adventure activities that SafetyWing doesn't—motorcycles, diving beyond basic limits, climbing. Trip protection included. Higher coverage limits available. Can extend while abroad.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Trip-based rather than subscription (less flexible). More expensive than SafetyWing. Still travel medical, not comprehensive. Age limits apply.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nomads who surf, dive, ride motorcycles, or otherwise need adventure activity coverage.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cigna Global — Best Comprehensive Nomad Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The good:</strong> Real international health insurance, not travel medical. Routine care, chronic conditions, mental health all covered. Meets any visa requirement. 1.5M+ provider network with direct billing. Telemedicine platform works anywhere.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Annual commitment, not monthly subscription. Higher cost ($150-350/month). Less flexible than nomad-specific options. Requires declaring area of coverage.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Nomads who need comprehensive coverage—those with health conditions, older nomads, or those wanting real health insurance rather than emergency coverage.
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <CTABox
    title="Living the Nomad Life?"
    description="Get coverage that moves with you. Compare plans designed for location independence."
    buttonText="Compare Nomad Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/safetywing"
  />

  <h2 id="nomad-needs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">What Digital Nomads Need</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">No Fixed Address Required</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Traditional expat insurance asks where you live. Nomads often can't answer that. Good nomad insurance doesn't require a permanent address, country of residence, or fixed location. You're covered wherever you go.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Month-to-Month Flexibility</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Plans change. You might extend in Lisbon, cut Bali short, or suddenly head home. Monthly subscription models let you match coverage to your actual timeline. No penalty for changing plans.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Worldwide Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Nomads move between regions. Coverage that works only in Europe or only in Asia creates gaps. Worldwide coverage (excluding perhaps the US, for cost reasons) keeps you protected everywhere.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Home Country Visits</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Even nomads go home sometimes—family visits, visa runs, life events. Coverage should include home country visits rather than excluding them entirely. SafetyWing includes 30 days per 90-day period.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Telemedicine Access</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    When you're in a new country, finding a doctor is challenging. Telemedicine—video calling a doctor who speaks your language—is your first line of care. Essential for nomadic healthcare access.
  </p>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Digital Nomad Visa Requirements</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Insurance as Visa Requirement</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Most digital nomad visas require proof of health insurance. Portugal, Spain, Croatia, Estonia, Greece, and others all mandate coverage. Your insurance must meet their specific requirements to qualify.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">What Countries Require</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Requirements vary but typically include: minimum coverage amounts (often €30,000+), coverage valid in the destination country, and sometimes specific inclusions like repatriation. Most nomad-focused insurance meets these requirements.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Getting Documentation</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Visa applications need insurance certificates showing your name, coverage dates, coverage amounts, and covered territory. SafetyWing, Genki, and others provide visa-ready documentation. Request it during application.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Specific Country Notes</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Portugal and Spain accept most nomad insurance. Germany has stricter requirements—SafetyWing may not qualify; Genki or local options work better. Research your specific destination's requirements. See our <a href="/visas/digital-nomad-visa/in/portugal" class="text-primary-600 hover:underline">visa guides</a> for country-specific details.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Applying for a Digital Nomad Visa?"
    description="Get insurance that meets your visa requirements. We'll help you find compliant coverage."
    buttonText="Find Visa-Compliant Coverage"
    buttonHref="/go/safetywing"
  />

  <h2 id="location-independence" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">True Location Independence</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Coverage That Follows You</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Switch countries without switching insurance. No need to notify your insurer when you fly from Mexico to Portugal. Coverage works automatically wherever you go (within covered territories).
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">No "Primary Residence" Requirement</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Traditional expat plans ask for your country of residence. If you're truly nomadic, you don't have one. Nomad-specific insurance accepts this reality rather than forcing you into categories that don't fit.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Claims from Anywhere</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    File claims online, get reimbursements to international bank accounts, handle everything digitally. You shouldn't need to be in a specific country to manage your insurance.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Time Zone Flexibility</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Customer service and telemedicine should work regardless of your time zone. 24/7 availability matters when you're 12 hours offset from your insurer's headquarters.
  </p>

  <h2 id="tech-lifestyle" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Tech and Lifestyle Coverage</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Laptop Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Your laptop is your livelihood. Some travel insurance includes electronics coverage, but limits are often low ($500-1,000). For expensive equipment, consider separate gadget insurance or higher-limit policies.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Coworking and Cafe Life</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Nomad life means cafes, coworking spaces, and varied work environments. Standard health insurance doesn't care where you work. But if theft or accidents happen in these settings, verify your policy covers them.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Adventure Activities</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Many nomads combine work with adventure—surfing before work, hiking on weekends, motorcycle transportation. Verify your activities are covered. SafetyWing has limitations; World Nomads covers more.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Mental Health</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Nomad life has mental health challenges—isolation, constant change, lack of routine. Travel medical insurance typically doesn't cover mental health. If this matters, comprehensive coverage becomes valuable.
  </p>

  <h2 id="common-mistakes" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Assuming Travel Insurance Is Enough</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Regular travel insurance assumes you have home country coverage and are traveling temporarily. Nomads often have neither. Nomad-specific insurance recognizes this.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Ignoring Pre-Existing Conditions</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Travel medical excludes pre-existing conditions. If you have conditions requiring treatment, you need comprehensive coverage, not nomad travel insurance. Don't discover this during a health crisis.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Not Checking Visa Requirements</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Just because SafetyWing works in most countries doesn't mean it meets every visa requirement. Germany, for example, has stricter rules. Check before applying.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Letting Coverage Lapse</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    With subscription models, it's easy to accidentally let coverage lapse. Set reminders. Auto-renewal helps. A gap in coverage during an emergency is devastating.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Underinsuring for Adventure Activities</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    A motorcycle accident in Vietnam without proper coverage can cost $50,000+. Medical evacuation from remote areas costs $100,000+. Make sure your activities are actually covered.
  </p>

  <h2 id="choosing-plan" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Choosing the Right Plan</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Young, Healthy, Flexible</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    SafetyWing is the default choice. $42/month, subscription flexibility, works everywhere. For most healthy nomads under 40, this is the sweet spot of coverage and cost.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Adventure-Focused</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    If surfing, diving, motorcycles, or climbing are part of your life, World Nomads covers activities SafetyWing doesn't. The extra cost is worth it if you need that coverage.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Europe-Based</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Genki offers a European alternative with good pricing and coverage. For nomads spending most time in Europe, it's worth comparing to SafetyWing.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Need Real Health Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Older nomads, those with health conditions, or anyone wanting comprehensive coverage should look at Cigna Global or similar. Higher cost but real health insurance rather than emergency coverage.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Families</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    SafetyWing includes two children free per adult—excellent value for nomad families. For families needing comprehensive coverage, Cigna Global family plans work well.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Get Covered?"
    description="Find insurance that matches your nomad lifestyle. Compare options in minutes."
    buttonText="Compare Nomad Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/safetywing"
  />

  <h2 id="faqs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What's the best insurance for digital nomads?</h3>
      <p>SafetyWing is the most popular choice—affordable ($42/month), flexible (monthly subscription), and designed specifically for nomads. For adventure activities, World Nomads. For comprehensive coverage, Cigna Global.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Does SafetyWing meet visa requirements?</h3>
      <p>For most digital nomad visas, yes. Portugal, Spain, Croatia, and many others accept SafetyWing. Germany has stricter requirements that SafetyWing may not meet. Always verify for your specific destination.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I sign up after leaving my home country?</h3>
      <p>Yes. SafetyWing and similar nomad insurance let you sign up from anywhere. You don't need to be in your home country to start coverage. This is a key difference from traditional travel insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What about pre-existing conditions?</h3>
      <p>Travel medical insurance (SafetyWing, World Nomads, Genki) excludes pre-existing conditions. If you have conditions requiring regular treatment, you need comprehensive international health insurance like Cigna Global.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is motorcycle riding covered?</h3>
      <p>SafetyWing covers motorcycles under 125cc. World Nomads covers larger motorcycles with proper license and helmet. Always verify before renting—motorcycle accidents are a leading cause of nomad injuries.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Do I need insurance if I'm only abroad for a few months?</h3>
      <p>Yes. Medical emergencies don't check your travel duration. A few months without coverage is a few months of risk. Short-term coverage is affordable—there's no reason to go without.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mt-12">
    This information is for educational purposes. Coverage details and visa requirements vary. Verify specific terms with insurers and check current visa requirements for your destinations. Last updated: April 2026.
  </p>
</PageShell>
